Every year I ruin Columbus Day for my 10th grade US I class and sing the praise of Bartolome de las Casas...and I think your solution for the day is brilliant, and one I will share with my now completely disabused 10th graders. Happy Bartolome Day!

Having read all about the sadistic and depraved Christopher Columbus many years ago, and about the priest Bartolome de las Casas who tried desperately to save the Natives who were being savaged, I always wonder why Columbus Day is still celebrated in the US. It's like having a Hitler Day, really.

I'd rather have a national holiday remembering fellow indigenous people lost so that we can all be here. As a registered native, I get tired of seeing people honored who tried to "save" us when we all have a historical legacy of resistance ex. Sitting Bull, Red Cloud, Crazy Horse, are just a couple examples from me and my fellow Lakota bands, not to mention the countless others that fought against colonization and even  Columbus personally. I'd like to see a real, nationally and federally recognized holiday for our native leaders and people who gave up their lives and were killed so that you all can enjoy the land and country you live in.
Welp, another guy named Columbus pretty much discovered the clitoris in the mid 1500s.  I'm alright with celebrating that! http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Realdo_Colombo
The Oatmeal - Here is a petition I found about changing Columbus Day - http://www.change.org/petitions/president-obama-and-a-sitting-congress-remove-columbus-day-as-a-national-holiday
Well, you brought down Edison and pretty much built a god damn Tesla museum... You need to start a petition for this. You win at everything.
Best comparison ever:  "He discovered the New World much like a meteorite discovered the dinosaurs."
"Christopher Columbus left his home and found a new world. Bartolme de las Casas left his home and found his humanity." - Well said!

Historically, I have defended Colombus because his atrocities, though bad, were a product of his time. You, for the first point, have brought me to the other side of the fence by making the wonderful point that we should celebrate the figures that were great DESPITE their time. So thank you, Mr.Inman, as always your works have influenced me for the better.
I call it Indigenous Peoples Day and still wear my t-shirt from 1992 that reads: 500 Years of Resistance.
Not bad.  Considering my first homework assignment in college was to read "The destruction of the Indies" I'd support this move.

I love the line "Columbus discovered the New World much like a meteorite discovered the dinosaurs."  

Happy Bartolomé Day!

Yeah, you might want to read up on Abe Lincoln before declaring him to be a progressively minded role model. He didn't care about the black people. Freeing the slaves was great, sure, and certainly progressive for the time, but he was still a spiteful bigot who would have kept slavery if that would save the union. The Civil War was not about slavery.

Hi everyone,

I should point out that we aren't saying any costume isn't allowed, I'm certainly going to come down on the side of freedom of expression and speech, even when that is questionable. What I am hoping sharing this post will do is remind people to be sensitive to the feelings and concerns of others.

The fact that people of different cultures feel this way about "appropriation," and sometimes mockery in costumes is something I'd simply like people to think about.

I really am not looking for a divisive thread to begin here.

Wear what you like, but first I hope you'll take the time to consider the feelings of others.

And as I say that I have to cop to bring the guy who showed up at a "White Party" dressed as a Brown Shirt. Given that, I won't be quick to judge others on their costume choices.
viva la brown coats!
Is dressing up as a witch, satan, or an angel, sac religious now? It's a bit ridiculous. It's a costume!

i think it depends on the intention in the costume. 
some costumes reek of mockery, and others show adoration. BUT what would i know? i cant speak for others.

oh gezuz,, people need to lighten the fk up.  It's the notion that a costume is taken so seriously  which i find  upsetting.   people dress up as "goth" for Halloween and when I was a teen, a goth, the culture I felt I fit into. It never offended me.  Fine, maybe there's no ethic  element to it,. but  that's the whole point I am making.  this sort of stuff  just proliferates and exacerbates  separation rather than acceptance.  makes heavy something which should be light, accepted, and a non issue.  i went as gypsy when I was a kid for Halloween, does that mean I was being a racist 10 year old.. no, of course not. I wanted to be  gypsy for a day!   Dressing up is exploration, its fantasy, its for fun for christ sakes.. get a grip.

Thanks, Reive. This may not be a priority to everyone, and clearly not everyone may agree with it. But the reality of it is that people who have been oppressed take offence to people treating their people as costume opportunities. Kudos to you for drawing attention to their voices.

A very bubbly friend dressed as a Mistress of the night a couple years ago; black hair, lace, eyeliner etc..... she showed up at the party and people wouldn't stop coming up to me and saying "Hey Mya look! Jamie came as YOU!!!"

Silly.

Although the intent of the wearer matters, the feelings of the group of people represented matter more. While the line is, I believe grey, when dressing in clothing representative of other cultures, it is important to consider whether the people of that culture might perceive one's costume as demeaning to them. 

It is far too easy, as members of a dominant social group - one that may never have experienced racism - to say "Get a life". This fails to demonstrate the perspective taking necessary for empathy.

Here's an example that may ring a bit more true for this group... What if I, as a straight person, were to dress up in clothing considered stereotypically dyke-like, or campy gay. Not ok me thinks. Just a thought.

I think their slogan is a little confusing "This is not who I am and this is not ok." If it's not who you are, why do you care about it? Besides, dressing up as something "other" is sort of the pint to the commercial version of Halloween that exists these days. 

On a related note, should I be offended if someone dresses up as Guy Fawkes, Braveheart or Ned Kelly? What about as a pirate (I do have that UK-Caribbean heritage thing going on as well)?

Some of the objections brought up are addressed in the original link and the link provided by Marcella. Again, though, we have members of traditionally oppressed cultures indicating discomfort with non-oppressed cultures treating them as costume opportunities. Aren't there enough other choices to make rather than one that they find offensive? (And a response to possible reactions to that question is also found in the second link provided above).
Dave credit goes to you and Miss E for posting it to my feed!

What's the role of overconfidence in natural selection?

Assuming that over confidence will eventually result in death the purpose of over confidence would be to increase the chance of mating before death since there is no evolutionary pressure post mating. As far as evolution is concerned if you mate before dying then a successful bet was made.
